{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians --> | name = Len Spencer | image = Len_Spencer_1899.jpg | image_size = | landscape = | caption = | background = solo_singer | birth_name = Leonard Garfield Spencer | birth_date = {{Birth date|1867|2|12}} | birth_place = [[Washington, D.C.]], U.S. | death_date = {{death date|1914|12|15}} | death_place = New York City | genre = | occupation = Musician, songwriter | years_active = | label = | associated_acts = | module = {{Listen | filename = Advertising Record.ogg | title = '''Advertising Record''' | embed = yes | description = This 1906 record by Spencer enticed store customers with the wonders of the phonograph. }} }}
'''Leonard Garfield Spencer''' (February 12, 1867 – December 15, 1914) was an early American recording artist.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=November 1896|title=Mr. Leonard Spencer|url=https://archive.org/stream/phonoscope13hunt#page/n19/mode/1up|journal=The Phonoscope|volume= 1| issue = 1|pages=14}}</ref> He began recording for the [[Columbia Phonograph Company]], in 1889 or 1890.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=January 1930|title=Reminiscences of the Columbia Cylinder Records|url=https://archive.org/stream/PMR_4_4/4_4#page/n7/mode/1up|journal=Phonograph Monthly Review|volume= 4| issue = 4|pages=114–115}}</ref> Between 1892 and 1897 he recorded extensively for the New Jersey Phonograph Company and its successor the United States Phonograph Company.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Catalog of Standard New Jersey Records for the Phonograph|last=|first=|publisher=United States Phonograph Company|year=c. 1894|isbn=|location=https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/474deac0-e01b-0130-57cf-58d385a7b928|pages=33–41}}</ref> He specialized in vaudeville sketches and comic songs, but also sang sentimental ballads popular at the time.<ref name=":0" /> He returned to Columbia in 1898 for an exclusive contract<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=July 1898|title=Gallery of Talent Employed for Making Records|url=https://archive.org/stream/phonoscope13hunt#page/n313/mode/1up|journal=The Phonoscope|volume= 2| issue = 7|pages=12–13}}</ref> then began recording for [[Berliner Gramophone]] (disc) records in 1899 and continued with [[Victor Talking Machine Company|Victor]] and [[Columbia Phonograph|Columbia]] as discs became the dominant format in the early 1900s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adp.library.ucsb.edu/index.php/talent/detail/40774/Spencer_Len_vocalist_baritone_vocal|title=Len Spencer (vocalist : baritone vocal)|last=|first=|date=|website=Discography of American Historical Recordings|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
He began performing with banjoist [[Vess Ossman|Vess L. Ossman]] in 1901 and with [[Ada Jones]] in 1905. He is best remembered today for his vaudeville-style comic sketches, such as the "Arkansaw Traveler", combining clever turns of phrase, ironic elocutionary delivery, sound effects and music to create colorful dialogues featuring itinerant Southerners, auctioneers, circus barkers, and Irish, Jewish or Black Americans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adp.library.ucsb.edu/index.php/talent/detail/29858/Spencer_Len_author|title=Len Spencer (author)|last=|first=|date=|website=Discography of American Historical Recordings|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>
As the popularity of Len's style of humor waned in the latter part of the decade, he opened a booking agency called "Len Spencer's Lyceum" in New York.<ref name=":1" /> He died of a heart attack while working at the Lyceum on December 15, 1914.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Walsh|first=Jim|date=October 1958|title=Len Spencer, as his Daughter Ethel Lovingly Recalls Him|url=|journal=Hobbies Magazine|volume=|pages=30–35|note=}}</ref> [[File:Len_Spencer's_Lyceum.jpg|thumb|Advertisement for Len Spencer's Lyceum, ca. 1912.]]
==Songs== Some of his most popular recordings include: * "[[Ta-ra-ra Boom-de-ay|Ta-Ra-Ra-Boom Der E]]" (1892) * "[[The Old Folks at Home]]" (1892) * "[[Little Alabama Coon]]" (1895) * "[[Dat New Bully]]" (1895) * "[[A Hot Time in the Old Town]]" (1897) * "[[Hello! Ma Baby]]" (1899) * "Ma Tiger Lily" (1900) * "Arkansaw Traveler" (1902) * "Peaches and Cream", (1906) with Ada Jones (John B. Lowitz wax cylinder)<ref name=":1">Frank Hoffmann, B Lee Cooper, Tim Gracyk -Popular American Recording Pioneers: 1895-1925 - Page 188 1136592296 2012 -"She is called "Miss Ada Jones," though in Manhattan on August 9, 1904, she had married Hughie Flaherty...On various records the two imitated Bowery toughs (on the popular "Peaches and Cream," Spencer was a "newsy" named Jimmie..."</ref>
